photos.Observation Details: Pair feeding together.  Returning to the same perch (like a WWP) but fairly low perches for the most part.  Obviously paired.  Found after an hour of searching, about 200 yards up the canyon from the cairn.  They were working the south slope, perhaps 50-75 yds up the hillside in an area of partial sunshine and downed logs.
Well photographed

Found on tree snag at corner of Devereux and Slough Roads at 2:10 PM.   Spotted by Aaron Maizlish, Jared Dawson, Kathleen Boehm-Dawson.   The bird was flycatching actively.  We observed it for about seven minutes, it moved perches several times.    It responded to Jared's playback, flying down and toward him.  Eventually flew out of sight into the willows to the East.  We were unable to refind him.  The flickr photos are geo-referenced to the exact tree where found.  Though unmistakable as an OS Flycatcher (look at the sharp vest) we wanted to rule out Greater Pewee.  Has two toned bill, which does not show well in photo -but more are available.

photos.Observation Details: Heard just twice over 30 minutes, the distinctive three-note call, both times when a bunch of other birds were calling.  Finally tracked it down below the north 3-way junction at the ravine.  Photos.

Seen at the outer 'elbow' of the marina, in a bush that often gets weird migrants.   Empid had gray head, rounded - not peaked like a Pac Slope.  Fairly long bi-colored mandible.   Solid narrow white eye-ring that did not extend into a tear-drop in the back.   White breast with some yelllowish wash.  Very white wing bars.   Noticeably short wing tips, which I regard as diagnostic.   Continuous downward tail pump (I only know of this in Gray and Pac Slope.)   Fairly long tail.   Made a dry whit call, which was not familiar to me.   Did not respond to Pac Slope playback - I did not try Gray, since I didn't want to spook it.   There is very little suitable territory here and I assume it will be a one day wonder.

I found this pale empid at 37.743747, -122.414228 on the north side of Bernal Hill.  At first seeing it in only silhouette I was struck by its long thin bill and long dark tail, thought I might be looking at a gnatcatcher for a second.  Walked around to the bare tree where it was perching in the back.  Bird seemed to stick around for a couple of minutes at a time and then disappear for 10-15 minutes.   Though I assumed Gray, I ended up walking up the hill and down a treacherous, but busy, footpath over the tree so I could get better documentation.   Uniformly gray head, auricular and back with no contrast.  Whitish throat and faint yellow on belly.   From certain angles the auricular patch seemed to stand out - the lores extensive white, and has distinctive white tuft at the base of upper mandible, which I understand helps separate Gray from Dusky.   The most definitive characteristic is the oversize thin bill, black upper mandible, yellow lower slightly darker at the tip.  If not for the size of the bill I think this would be hard to separate visually from Dusky.  Head is rounded with a slight hint of a peak to the back.   Wings and tail feathers have a weathered look in the photos with spread-wings - not sure where this would be in the molt cycle, doesn't seem complete.    Wings are comparatively short, with wingtips and rest not extending as far as undertail coverts.  Tail dark.  I think the size, shape, color of bill, length of wingtips, and head shape cinch this as a Gray vs. Hammonds/Dusky.  Bird gave out a soft "chewit"-like dry whit call.  Pumped tail downward a bit, but not excessively.  I did not use playback.  Bird did not strike me as being particularly larger than the other empids.

thin complete eyering. white band across area just above bill (maxilla), grayish overall. mandible flesh-colored with dusky tip. soft, sharp "wit" calls were heard. the tail was lowered and then jerked more rapidly upward. primary projection relatively short for an Empidonax flycatcher.

photos.Observation Details: Pen-bird folks,  This afternoon around 2:30pm I found a good looking Tropical Kingbird at the Cypress Lawn Memorial Park in Colma.   The location was in the section of the cemetery that is south of El Camino Real, almost exactly where the Vermilion Flycatcher spent the winter of 2016-17.  This stretch is pretty birdy with flycatchers and thrushes.  The Tropical Kingbird was wide ranging, but came back several times to a perch near the top of a small yew(?) with dead branches on top.  He was also chased away a bit by the bluebirds, which were the only birds that seemed to mind his presence.  The yew tree was here 37.669597, -122.456826 though the flycatcher used the whole lawn.  Chris Hayward was nearby and we were able to refine the bird pretty quickly when he arrived.  Chris told me that Laurie Graham had one here in December, so I figure this bird has overwintered here.  Chris and I saw it fly off to the distance (toward the north), but I’ll bet it returns here frequently.
Wintering bird.  Looks imm.
